---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import siteData from '../data/site.json';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Vermont Property Tax Grievance | Grand List Challenge | VermontTaxAppeal.com"
  description="Vermont property tax grievances filed against the Grand List. We challenge town lister assessments before the Board of Civil Authority in Chittenden, Washington, Rutland, and all 14 VT counties. Contingency — no fee unless we save you money."
>

  <!-- HERO — narrative, plainspoken, Grand List-first -->
  <section class="relative min-h-[90vh] flex items-center overflow-hidden" style="background: #060a0f;">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 pointer-events-none">
      <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-[600px] h-[400px] opacity-10"
           style="background: radial-gradient(ellipse, #f97316 0%, transparent 70%);"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="relative max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 py-24 w-full">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">

        <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-full border border-orange-500/20 bg-orange-500/5 text-orange-400 text-xs font-semibold mb-10 tracking-wide">
          Vermont Grand List · BCA · All 14 Counties · No-Win No-Fee
        </div>

        <h1 class="text-5xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-black text-white leading-[1.06] mb-8" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          Vermont sets<br />
          your property value<br />
          on the <span style="background: linear-gradient(90deg, #f97316, #fb923c); -webkit-background-clip: text; -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent; background-clip: text;">Grand List.</span><br />
          <span class="text-slate-300" style="font-size: 0.75em;">You can dispute it.</span>
        </h1>

        <p class="text-slate-300 text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed mb-5 max-w-2xl">
          Every spring, Vermont towns file the Grand List — the official record of assessed values for every parcel in the municipality. If your property is listed too high, you have a window to file a written grievance with the town listers under Vermont statute 32 V.S.A. § 4404.
        </p>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-base leading-relaxed mb-10 max-w-2xl">
          Most people don't. Most overpay as a result. We handle the grievance from start to finish — lister hearing, Board of Civil Authority appeal, everything — at no cost unless we get your value reduced.
        </p>

        <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 mb-14">
          <a href="/contact" class="px-8 py-4 text-sm btn-orange inline-flex items-center gap-2 justify-center font-semibold">
            Get a Free Grievance Review
            <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4"/></svg>
          </a>
          <a href="/how-it-works" class="px-8 py-4 text-sm btn-ghost inline-flex items-center gap-2 justify-center">
            How Vermont Grievances Work
          </a>
        </div>

        <!-- Vermont State House image — plainspoken local anchor -->
        <div class="rounded-2xl overflow-hidden relative" style="max-width: 540px; height: 200px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.07);">
          <img
            src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Vermont_State_House_2009.jpg/800px-Vermont_State_House_2009.jpg"
            alt="Vermont State House Montpelier VT — Vermont property tax law and Grand List process"
            width="800"
            height="200"
            loading="eager"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
            style="filter: brightness(0.72) saturate(0.9);"
          />
          <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 right-0 px-4 py-2" style="background: linear-gradient(transparent, rgba(6,10,15,0.9));">
            <span class="text-xs text-slate-500">Vermont State House, Montpelier — where Vermont's property tax statutes live</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TRUST STRIP -->
  <div style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.015); border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06);" class="py-4">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-x-10 gap-y-3">
      {[
        'Vermont Grand List Specialist',
        'Grievance → BCA → State Appraiser',
        'No Win, No Fee',
        'All 14 Vermont Counties',
        'Residential & Commercial',
      ].map((item: string) => (
        <span class="text-slate-400 text-sm font-medium">✓ {item}</span>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HOW THE GRAND LIST WORKS — narrative explanation, VT-specific -->
  <section class="py-28 px-6" style="background: #060a0f;">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-16 items-start">
        <div>
          <p class="text-orange-400 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-4">How Vermont Property Tax Works</p>
          <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-white leading-tight mb-6">
            The Grand List is filed.<br />
            <span style="background: linear-gradient(90deg, #f97316, #fb923c); -webkit-background-clip: text; -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent; background-clip: text;">Then comes your window.</span>
          </h2>
          <p class="text-slate-300 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-5">
            Vermont towns are required to assess property at fair market value. Each year the town listers prepare the Grand List, typically finalized by April 1. Once filed, you have 30 days to contest your assessed value by filing a written grievance under 32 V.S.A. § 4404.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed mb-5">
            In practice, that window is narrow. Listers in Burlington, Montpelier, Rutland, and towns across Chittenden and Washington counties work from mass appraisal models that don't account for what's actually happening inside your building — deferred maintenance, a difficult lease structure, vacancy, or income shortfalls that the wider market hasn't priced in yet.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            A properly documented grievance — backed by an income analysis or comparable sales that speak to your specific property — changes that equation. Most of our cases settle at the lister or Board of Civil Authority level, before anything goes to the Director of Property Valuation and Review.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Vermont rural property / BCA image -->
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="rounded-2xl overflow-hidden" style="height: 270px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06);">
            <img
              src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Burlington%2C_Vermont_-_Church_Street_Marketplace.jpg/800px-Burlington%2C_Vermont_-_Church_Street_Marketplace.jpg"
              alt="Burlington Vermont Church Street — Chittenden County commercial property tax assessment area"
              width="800"
              height="270"
              loading="lazy"
              class="w-full h-full object-cover"
              style="filter: brightness(0.72) saturate(0.9);"
              onerror="this.parentElement.style.background='rgba(249,115,22,0.04)'; this.style.display='none';"
            />
            <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 right-0 px-4 py-2" style="background: linear-gradient(transparent, rgba(6,10,15,0.9));">
              <span class="text-xs text-slate-500">Church Street, Burlington VT — Chittenden County is Vermont's highest-value commercial market</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div class="rounded-xl p-5" style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.07);">
              <div class="text-orange-400 font-black text-xl mb-1">30 Days</div>
              <div class="text-slate-400 text-xs leading-relaxed">After the Grand List is filed to submit your written grievance under 32 V.S.A. § 4404. The window closes fast.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-xl p-5" style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.07);">
              <div class="text-orange-400 font-black text-xl mb-1">1.5%–2.2%</div>
              <div class="text-slate-400 text-xs leading-relaxed">Effective Vermont property tax rates. On a $900K commercial building, that's $13,500–$20K+ per year in property taxes alone.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- VT GRIEVANCE PROCESS — step by step, plainspoken -->
  <section class="py-28 px-6" style="background: #04080f;">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
      <div class="mb-14">
        <p class="text-orange-400 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">The Vermont Grievance Path</p>
        <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-white mb-4">Grievance → BCA → State Appraiser</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-lg max-w-2xl">Vermont has three stages of formal review. Most cases resolve at the first or second. We take every case as far as it needs to go.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        {[
          {
            num: '01',
            statute: '32 V.S.A. § 4404',
            title: 'Grievance Filed with Town Listers',
            body: "The first step is a written grievance submitted to the town listers within 30 days of the Grand List being filed — usually by late April or early May depending on the municipality. We prepare the grievance, assemble the evidence package (comparable sales, income analysis, condition documentation), and attend the lister hearing on your behalf. For properties in Burlington, Montpelier, St. Albans, or smaller towns in Lamoille and Orange counties, the lister stage is where good cases often settle.",
            tag: '30-Day Window'
          },
          {
            num: '02',
            statute: '32 V.S.A. § 4461',
            title: 'Board of Civil Authority Hearing',
            body: "If the listers don't move the value, we appeal to the Board of Civil Authority — the BCA. This is a formal hearing before the BCA, which typically includes the town clerk and a rotating panel of selectboard members. The BCA conducts a site inspection and reviews the full evidence record. Vermont property owners have a statutory right to present additional evidence at the BCA stage beyond what was introduced at the lister level.",
            tag: 'BCA Hearing'
          },
          {
            num: '03',
            statute: '32 V.S.A. § 4467',
            title: 'Director of Property Valuation and Review',
            body: "If the BCA decision leaves value on the table, the next level is an appeal to the Director of Property Valuation and Review — the state appraiser. This level involves a de novo hearing and a more formal evidence presentation. The Director's decisions create precedent that influences future assessments across Vermont municipalities.",
            tag: 'State Appeal'
          },
          {
            num: '04',
            statute: '32 V.S.A. § 4462',
            title: 'Superior Court — Final Stage',
            body: "Appeals from the Director's decision can be taken to Vermont Superior Court. This is the final level of administrative review. We escalate to this stage only when the numbers clearly justify it — but it's available, and we know how to use it.",
            tag: 'Court Level'
          },
        ].map((step: {num:string,statute:string,title:string,body:string,tag:string}) => (
          <div style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(249,115,22,0.1); border-radius: 14px; padding: 24px 28px;">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
              <div class="shrink-0 text-center">
                <div class="text-4xl font-black text-orange-500/25 leading-none mb-2">{step.num}</div>
                <div class="text-orange-400 font-bold text-xs border border-orange-500/30 rounded px-2 py-0.5">{step.statute}</div>
              </div>
              <div class="flex-1">
                <div class="flex items-start justify-between gap-3 flex-wrap mb-2">
                  <h3 class="text-white font-bold text-base">{step.title}</h3>
                  <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-slate-500 border border-slate-700 rounded px-2 py-1 shrink-0">{step.tag}</span>
                </div>
                <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">{step.body}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RESULTS — VT-specific, named towns -->
  <section class="py-24 px-6" style="background: #060a0f;">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
      <div class="mb-12">
        <p class="text-orange-400 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">What Success Looks Like</p>
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black text-white mb-3">Vermont Grievances That Worked</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-400 max-w-xl">Real results from Vermont property owners who challenged the Grand List. Every one of these turned on Vermont-specific evidence — not a generic template.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-5">
        {[
          {
            quote: "Our Burlington rental on North Street was listed on the Grand List at a value that assumed full market rents. Our leases were two years old and below the current market — the tenants were good, we didn't push for increases. The lister's model didn't know that. We filed a grievance under 32 V.S.A. § 4404, built an income analysis using our actual rent roll, and the BCA reduced the Grand List value by $74,000.",
            name: "Paul & Anna T.",
            detail: "Burlington, VT · Rental · Chittenden County",
            result: "Grand List reduced $74,000",
            initial: "P"
          },
          {
            quote: "The town of Stowe had reassessed our commercial lodge property during a statewide reappraisal year. The new value came in $310,000 higher than we expected based on comparable sales in the area. We pulled eight arm's-length sales of similar lodging properties in Lamoille County from the prior 24 months. The BCA found our comp set more credible than the lister's cost-approach estimate.",
            name: "Green Peak Lodging LLC",
            detail: "Stowe, VT · Commercial lodge · Lamoille County",
            result: "Reappraisal overridden at BCA",
            initial: "G"
          },
          {
            quote: "Our Montpelier commercial building had a vacant first-floor retail unit for eleven months. The Grand List value was set as if the space was occupied. Vermont law recognizes income losses from sustained vacancies as a valuation factor. We documented the vacancy, the marketing efforts, and the net operating income shortfall. The lister agreed and adjusted the value.",
            name: "Capital District Properties",
            detail: "Montpelier, VT · Retail/Office · Washington County",
            result: "Settled at lister stage",
            initial: "C"
          }
        ].map((t: {quote:string,name:string,detail:string,result:string,initial:string}) => (
          <div style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06); border-radius: 16px; padding: 26px;">
            <p style="color:#94a3b8; font-size:0.88rem; line-height:1.75; font-style:italic; margin-bottom:18px;">"{t.quote}"</p>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
              <div style="width:38px; height:38px; border-radius:50%; background:linear-gradient(135deg,#f97316,#ea580c); display:flex; align-items:center; justify-content:center; color:#fff; font-weight:900; font-size:0.88rem; flex-shrink:0;">{t.initial}</div>
              <div>
                <div style="font-size:0.85rem; font-weight:700; color:#e2e8f0;">{t.name}</div>
                <div style="font-size:0.72rem; color:#64748b;">{t.detail}</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div style="background:rgba(249,115,22,0.08); border:1px solid rgba(249,115,22,0.2); border-radius:8px; padding:8px 13px; font-size:0.78rem; font-weight:700; color:#fb923c;">✓ {t.result}</div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PROPERTY TYPES -->
  <section class="py-20 px-6" style="background: #04080f;">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
      <div class="text-center mb-10">
        <p class="text-orange-400 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">Property Types We Represent</p>
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-white mb-3">If It's on the Grand List, It Can Be Grieved</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-400 max-w-md mx-auto text-sm">Vermont grievance rights apply equally to residential and commercial property under 32 V.S.A. § 4404.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-6 gap-3">
        {[
          { icon: '🏠', label: 'Single Family', sub: 'Year-round & seasonal' },
          { icon: '🏘️', label: 'Multi-Family', sub: 'Duplexes, apartments' },
          { icon: '🏢', label: 'Commercial', sub: 'Office, retail, mixed-use' },
          { icon: '🏭', label: 'Industrial', sub: 'Manufacturing, storage' },
          { icon: '🏔️', label: 'Ski & Resort', sub: 'Lodges, ski-in properties' },
          { icon: '🌾', label: 'Agricultural', sub: 'Farm, current use land' },
        ].map((p: {icon:string,label:string,sub:string}) => (
          <div style="background:rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06); border-radius:12px; padding:18px; text-align:center;">
            <div class="text-3xl mb-2">{p.icon}</div>
            <div class="text-white font-bold text-sm mb-1">{p.label}</div>
            <div class="text-slate-500 text-xs">{p.sub}</div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COUNTIES -->
  <section class="py-16 px-6" style="background: #060a0f;">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
      <div class="text-center mb-8">
        <p class="text-orange-400 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">Where We File</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-white mb-2">All 14 Vermont Counties</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">From Chittenden and Washington to Essex and Grand Isle — every county, every municipality.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 justify-center">
        {siteData.targetCounties.map((county: string) => (
          <a href={`/counties/${county.toLowerCase().replace(/ /g, '-')}-county`}
             class="text-xs font-semibold text-slate-400 border border-slate-700 rounded px-3 py-1.5 hover:border-orange-500/50 hover:text-orange-400 transition-all">
            {county} County
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- VERMONT GOVERNMENT RESOURCES -->
  <section class="py-16 px-6" style="background: #04080f;">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
      <div class="text-center mb-8">
        <p class="text-orange-400 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">Vermont Government Resources</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-white mb-2">Official Grievance & Tax Authority</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        <a href="https://sos.vermont.gov/municipal-division/boards-of-civil-authority/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.07); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; transition: all 0.3s ease;" class="hover:border-orange-500/30 group">
          <div class="text-white font-bold text-sm mb-2">Board of Civil Authority</div>
          <p class="text-slate-500 text-xs leading-relaxed">Vermont Secretary of State municipal division guide to BCA procedures and jurisdiction.</p>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-1 text-orange-400 text-xs font-semibold mt-3 group-hover:gap-2 transition-all">
            Visit <svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4"/></svg>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="https://tax.vermont.gov/property/property-tax-adjustment" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.07); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; transition: all 0.3s ease;" class="hover:border-orange-500/30 group">
          <div class="text-white font-bold text-sm mb-2">Vermont Department of Taxes</div>
          <p class="text-slate-500 text-xs leading-relaxed">Official Vermont property tax adjustment and grievance filing procedures.</p>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-1 text-orange-400 text-xs font-semibold mt-3 group-hover:gap-2 transition-all">
            Visit <svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4"/></svg>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="https://legislature.vermont.gov/statutes/section/32VSA/04404" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.07); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; transition: all 0.3s ease;" class="hover:border-orange-500/30 group">
          <div class="text-white font-bold text-sm mb-2">Vermont Statute 32 V.S.A. § 4404</div>
          <p class="text-slate-500 text-xs leading-relaxed">Official Vermont statutory text governing property tax grievances and the 30-day filing deadline.</p>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-1 text-orange-400 text-xs font-semibold mt-3 group-hover:gap-2 transition-all">
            View Law <svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4"/></svg>
          </div>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ — VT-specific, statute-referenced, plainspoken tone -->
  <section class="py-24 px-6" style="background: #04080f;">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <div class="mb-12">
        <p class="text-orange-400 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">What People Ask</p>
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-white">Vermont Grand List Grievances — Plain Answers</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="space-y-2">
        {[
          { q: 'When exactly is the Vermont grievance deadline?', a: 'You have 30 days after the Grand List is lodged by the town listers — typically mid-April to mid-May, depending on the municipality. Under 32 V.S.A. § 4404, this deadline is set by the town\'s Grand List filing date, not by a fixed calendar date. Call your town clerk by early March to get the exact date for your town. We recommend contacting us no later than February.' },
          { q: "What is the Board of Civil Authority, and what does it actually do?", a: "The BCA is the first formal appeal body under 32 V.S.A. § 4461. It typically consists of the town clerk and members of the selectboard. The BCA conducts a site inspection of your property and reviews the full evidence record — both what was presented at the lister stage and any new evidence you introduce. BCA hearings are informal by court standards but substantive. A well-prepared case carries real weight here." },
          { q: "Can I grieve my Vermont property taxes every year?", a: "Yes. Under Vermont law, you have the right to grieve your assessment on every new Grand List — which is filed annually. Many of our Vermont clients do this year over year. We track your assessed value each cycle and reach out when the numbers look worth contesting again." },
          { q: "Does Vermont use a statewide reappraisal process?", a: "Vermont has a state-mandated reappraisal program under 32 V.S.A. § 4041a. When a town's common level of appraisal (CLA) falls below 80% of fair market value, the state can require or conduct a reappraisal. Statewide reappraisal years often produce significant value changes — and significant grievance opportunities. Towns like Barre, St. Johnsbury, and others in Caledonia and Orange counties have been through recent reappraisals." },
          { q: "What does the grievance contingency actually look like?", a: "We charge 30% of the first-year tax savings we achieve. If your annual Vermont property tax bill drops by $3,000 as a result of a successful grievance, our fee is $900. You keep the rest — and the full savings in every year after. If we don't get a reduction, you owe nothing at all." },
          { q: "What's the difference between a grievance and an abatement in Vermont?", a: "In Vermont, a grievance challenges your assessed value — the number on the Grand List. An abatement is a separate process for correcting a tax bill due to error, disaster loss, or exemption (32 V.S.A. § 3845). Most overpayment situations are resolved through a grievance, not an abatement. We handle both, but if you believe your assessment is too high, grievance is the right path." },
        ].map((item: {q:string,a:string}, i: number) => (
          <details style="background:rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.07); border-radius:12px;" class="group" id={`faq-${i}`}>
            <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer list-none">
              <span class="text-white font-semibold text-sm pr-4">{item.q}</span>
              <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-slate-500 shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <path d="M8 3v10M3 8h10"/>
              </svg>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed border-t pt-4" style="border-color:rgba(255,255,255,0.06);">{item.a}</div>
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
